10:03.236 --> 10:04.938 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and on that side.

10:04.971 --> 10:09.609 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You look at Hillary Clinton, she
stands in
much better shape, and the
organizational

10:09.642 --> 10:12.212 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
efforts who are going to be
important for
her.

10:12.245 --> 10:15.815 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I think she is primed to do
very well
on election night.

10:15.849 --> 10:17.650 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: How do you see
it, Whit?

10:17.684 --> 10:21.254 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WHIT AYRES, Republican Pollster:
If you look
at an average of recent polls,
Judy, Hillary

10:21.287 --> 10:24.791 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Clinton is ahead by about 6
percentage points.

10:24.824 --> 10:31.431 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
To put that in perspective, Mitt
Romney lost
to Barack Obama in 2012 by four
points, and

10:31.464 --> 10:35.635 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
John McCain lost to Barack Obama
in 2008 by
seven points.

10:35.668 --> 10:40.640 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, the deficit now is somewhere
between the
2008 and 2012 numbers.

10:40.673 --> 10:44.744 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, Peter, if
people watching
want to know, OK, who and what
are contributing

10:44.777 --> 10:48.882 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to her doing well and his not
doing as well,
how would you describe that?

10:48.915 --> 10:54.387 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PETER HART: Well, she has
broadened beyond
the traditional Democratic
coalition, and

10:54.420 --> 10:56.623 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
she's reaching across to
independents.

10:56.656 --> 11:00.059 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But she's doing exceptionally
well with women
at this stage in the game.

11:00.093 --> 11:06.833 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think that all the troubles
that Donald
Trump has had and his
difficulties have parlayed

11:06.866 --> 11:11.771 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a situation where independent
women are moving
across.

11:11.804 --> 11:18.578 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, also, women who have
college education,
that vote went for Romney four
years ago.

11:18.611 --> 11:20.680 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It certainly is going to be
Democratic this
time around.

11:20.713 --> 11:21.915 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And non-white.

11:21.948 --> 11:25.752 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PETER HART: Oh, definitely the
non-white voters
are there.

11:25.785 --> 11:27.720 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And the millennials are also
very strong.

11:27.754 --> 11:29.889 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Whit, what about
Donald Trump?

11:29.923 --> 11:31.758 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Where is he doing well and where
is he struggling?

11:31.791 --> 11:37.664 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WHIT AYRES: Donald Trump has
based his entire
campaign on getting a higher
turnout of whites

11:37.697 --> 11:40.133 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and getting a large proportion
of whites.

11:40.166 --> 11:45.872 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The problem with that is that
every single
presidential election since
1996, the proportion

11:45.905 --> 11:50.209 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of whites has gone down by two,
three, or
four percentage point.

11:50.243 --> 11:55.114 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This year will probably be about
70 percent
white and 30 percent non-white.

11:55.148 --> 12:00.620 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But trying to win a national
election in this
environment by getting a larger
and larger

12:00.653 --> 12:06.225 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
share of a smaller and smaller
proportion
of the electorate is a losing
strategic proposition.

12:06.259 --> 12:10.263 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Having said that,
Peter, you
come, as we said, from
conducting this focus

12:10.296 --> 12:13.299 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
group last night, undecided
voters, Charlotte,
North Carolina.

12:13.333 --> 12:14.300 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
PETER HART: Late deciders.

12:14.334 --> 12:15.268 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Late deciders.

12:15.301 --> 12:17.070 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
PETER HART: OK.

12:17.103 --> 12:21.140 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So these are people who waited
until after
the convention and have now
jumped in, and

12:21.174 --> 12:23.309 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
some of them still remain
undecided.

12:23.343 --> 12:29.115 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what's so fascinating is, we
started the
race where people were unhappy
with the world.

12:29.148 --> 12:33.620 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They remain unhappy with the
world, but they're
more unhappy with the
candidates.

12:33.653 --> 12:38.091 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I mean, they look at one as
unfit and the
other as untrustworthy.

12:38.124 --> 12:44.030 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, these poor people are
reaching the end
of the road, and, essentially,
they don't

12:44.063 --> 12:46.099 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
know what to do.

12:46.132 --> 12:50.536 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The interesting thing is, there
were three
women in the group, all of whom
should be

12:50.570 --> 12:56.943 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in the Republican column, and
they would like
to be there, but they just
cannot stomach

12:56.976 --> 12:57.944 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Donald Trump.

12:57.977 --> 13:00.546 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
They don't find him as
acceptable.

13:00.580 --> 13:02.048 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They find him as a bully.

13:02.081 --> 13:03.816 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
They find him as a baby.

13:03.850 --> 13:07.153 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They just -- everything about
him bothers
them.

13:07.186 --> 13:08.988 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So they can't be with him.

13:09.022 --> 13:12.725 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, Whit, have we
seen anything
-- have you seen anything like
this in your

13:12.759 --> 13:14.527 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
years of polling?

13:14.560 --> 13:18.431 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WHIT AYRES: We have never seen
anything like
Donald Trump before and probably
won't for

13:18.464 --> 13:19.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the rest of our lives.

13:19.699 --> 13:20.667 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

13:20.700 --> 13:22.502 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WHIT AYRES: It's amazing,
though, Judy.

13:22.535 --> 13:27.073 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Two-thirds of the people in this
country are
unsatisfied with the direction
of the country.

13:27.106 --> 13:28.875 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
They want a change.

13:28.908 --> 13:33.046 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You would think that Donald
Trump would be
able to tap into that
successfully, but he

13:33.079 --> 13:38.718 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
has run his entire campaign
preaching to the
converted and trashing everyone
else.

13:38.751 --> 13:44.257 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Consequently, he basically is
ending the campaign
right where he started it,
somewhere in the

13:44.290 --> 13:46.192 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
low 40s.

13:46.225 --> 13:53.066 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so a general election
strategy that involves
revving up your own supporters,
but not reaching

13:53.099 --> 13:54.934 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
out, is not a successful
strategy.

13:54.967 --> 13:58.738 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, Peter, back
to this question
about where the race is overall,
is there

13:58.771 --> 14:01.808 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a path to victory for Donald
Trump at this
point?

14:01.841 --> 14:03.509 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
PETER HART: No.

14:03.543 --> 14:04.777 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
And I say that.

14:04.811 --> 14:07.880 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Obviously, turnout is critical.

14:07.914 --> 14:14.487 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And African-Americans are less
enthusiastic
than they were in 2008 and 2012.

14:14.520 --> 14:19.392 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Hispanics are -- seem to be as
interested,
millennials much less
interested.

14:19.425 --> 14:23.730 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, I think Barack Obama becomes
the key to
this.

14:23.763 --> 14:30.970 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He has been an exceptional
surrogate, and
essentially bringing across
those voters.

14:31.003 --> 14:36.542 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think Michelle Obama has
become sort
of the moral center of this
campaign, and

14:36.576 --> 14:39.946 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
there's nobody that we have
found that is
more popular.

14:39.979 --> 14:45.651 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I actually think the Obamas
become the
legacy and the reason that
Hillary Clinton

14:45.685 --> 14:46.652 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
can win.

14:46.686 --> 14:47.920 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Whit, what do you
see?

14:47.954 --> 14:50.423 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Do you see there's a path of
some kind for
Donald Trump?

14:50.456 --> 14:53.192 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WHIT AYRES: It would be like
drawing an inside
straight.

14:53.226 --> 14:58.598 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He would have to win every
single swing state
that's remotely close right now,
and that's

14:58.631 --> 15:01.868 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a very, very high hill to climb
with less
than two weeks to go.

15:01.901 --> 15:07.540 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Whit, you were
also telling
us that -- something that
strikes but this

15:07.573 --> 15:12.578 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
election year is the separation
between what
you call the Trump brand and the
Republican

15:12.612 --> 15:13.579 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
brand.

15:13.613 --> 15:15.314 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What did you mean by that?

15:15.348 --> 15:17.016 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WHIT AYRES: There's a dramatic
difference
between the Trump brand and the
Republican

15:17.049 --> 15:20.219 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
brand, in part because Trump is
not really
a Republican.

15:20.253 --> 15:22.688 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What that means for down-ballot
races is...

15:22.722 --> 15:24.457 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: The Senate and
the House.

15:24.490 --> 15:26.926 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WHIT AYRES: Yes, the Senate and
the House,
is that a lot of Republican
candidates are

15:26.959 --> 15:31.097 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
running well ahead of Donald
Trump, even in
these swing states.

15:31.130 --> 15:36.903 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Candidates like Rob Portman in
Ohio, Marco
Rubio in Florida, Chuck Grassley
in Iowa,

15:36.936 --> 15:41.607 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
John McCain in Arizona are all
running well
ahead of Trump.

15:41.641 --> 15:47.246 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that is the hope that
Republicans have
that we could actually do well
in congressional

15:47.280 --> 15:49.215 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and Senate races.

15:49.248 --> 15:56.889 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It bears mentioning that when
Bob Dole lost
to Bill Clinton in 1996 by 8.5
points, Republicans

15:56.923 --> 15:58.624 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
picked up two Senate seats.

15:58.658 --> 15:59.959 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
So it's not unheard of.

15:59.992 --> 16:01.828 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Peter, how do you
see these
Senate races going?

16:01.861 --> 16:06.666 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PETER HART: Well, I think the
Senate is -- the
Republicans are having a very
difficult time,

16:06.699 --> 16:12.805 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
because they have so many seats
up, and the
mentions that Whit made are
important.

16:12.839 --> 16:15.308 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But you really have to go to a
different side
of it.

16:15.341 --> 16:20.279 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You look at so many of these
states, whether
it is Pennsylvania or New
Hampshire or even

16:20.313 --> 16:25.251 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
North Carolina and Wisconsin and
Illinois,
all of those seats are going to
be Democratic

16:25.284 --> 16:31.324 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
seats, in part because they will
have the
coattails of Hillary Clinton.

16:31.357 --> 16:33.159 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And you can add Missouri there.

16:33.192 --> 16:38.965 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I think the Democrats are
going to have
the majority, I think somewhere
in 51 to 52

16:38.998 --> 16:39.966 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
seats.

16:39.999 --> 16:41.434 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That would be my take.

16:41.467 --> 16:42.568 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WHIT AYRES: I'm not willing to
concede all
those seats today, Peter.

16:42.602 --> 16:43.703 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

16:43.736 --> 16:45.538 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WHIT AYRES: I think a lot of
them are very
close.

16:45.571 --> 16:49.742 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think Republicans are running
very good
campaigns for the Senate in
those -- in those

16:49.775 --> 16:51.577 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
states.

16:51.611 --> 16:55.448 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I am not giving up hope that
Republicans
can hold on to both the House
and the Senate.

16:55.481 --> 16:57.316 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
PETER HART: Underline hope.

16:57.350 --> 16:59.185 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

16:59.218 --> 17:02.088 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: We're going to
have you both
back after the election and look
at the numbers.

17:02.121 --> 17:03.589 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Peter Hart, Whit Ayres, thank
you both.

17:03.623 --> 17:04.590 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
WHIT AYRES: Thank you.

17:04.624 --> 17:05.858 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Enjoyed being with you.

17:05.892 --> 17:07.660 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Appreciate it.

17:07.693 --> 17:12.398 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Another big numbers focus during
this election
has been on money, how the
candidates have

17:12.431 --> 17:16.702 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
raised and spent it, and what
that says about
their campaigns.

17:16.736 --> 17:21.774 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Matea Gold covers money and
influence for
The Washington Post, and she
joins us now.

17:21.807 --> 17:23.542 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Matea, welcome back to the
program.

17:23.576 --> 17:28.281 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, tell us, what do we know at
this point
about what Donald Trump and
Hillary Clinton,

17:28.314 --> 17:30.249 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
how much they have raised and
how much they
have spent?

17:30.283 --> 17:33.986 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MATEA GOLD, The Washington Post:
So, what's
remarkable is that Hillary
Clinton has raised

17:34.020 --> 17:40.626 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
more than double Donald Trump,
and her campaign
committee, nearly $500 million,
to his $219

17:40.660 --> 17:41.827 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
million.

17:41.861 --> 17:45.398 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so she is by default also
vastly outspending
him.

17:45.431 --> 17:52.738 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In the month of September, she
plowed $95
million into her campaign
effort; $66 million

17:52.772 --> 17:56.642 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of that went into television ads
alone.

17:56.676 --> 18:01.447 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Donald Trump spent a third of
that on television
ads, as he's trying to really
build up his

18:01.480 --> 18:03.249 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
voter file.

18:03.282 --> 18:07.219 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We saw a lot of money going into
getting voter
data, but really he is getting
outflanked

18:07.253 --> 18:09.288 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
by Clinton on the money race in
every regard.

18:09.322 --> 18:13.859 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: What else can you
tell us,
Matea, about what they're
spending money on,

18:13.893 --> 18:15.795 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
staff organization,
get-out-the-vote?

18:15.828 --> 18:21.634 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MATEA GOLD: What is really
interesting is,
if you look at the campaign
spending strategy,

18:21.667 --> 18:24.704 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
you see a reflection of the
infrastructure
that they have invested in.

18:24.737 --> 18:31.944 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, Clinton, for example, had
815 staffers
on her payroll at the end of
September.

18:31.978 --> 18:36.816 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That's compared to 168 staffers
that Trump
had on his payroll.

18:36.849 --> 18:40.686 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what you see in there is the
investment
that Clinton is making in a
ground game.

18:40.720 --> 18:45.658 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She has staffers deployed all
across the country
in an effort to turn out the
vote.

18:45.691 --> 18:50.463 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Trump, on the other hand, is
leaning much
more heavily on the RNC to
provide that voter

18:50.496 --> 18:52.298 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
mobilization effort.

18:52.331 --> 18:56.302 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now, Matea, you
were telling
us, it's interesting to look at
how much Donald

18:56.335 --> 18:59.505 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Trump himself is putting into
his campaign.

18:59.538 --> 19:01.307 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What do you see in that regard?

19:01.340 --> 19:05.644 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MATEA GOLD: What's been very
curious is that
Trump continues to insist that
he's putting

19:05.678 --> 19:11.717 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
$100 million, if not more, into
his campaign
of his own personal funds.

19:11.751 --> 19:15.054 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
As of now, we have only seen $56
million.

19:15.087 --> 19:19.458 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
That's a large sum, but
obviously not close
to $100 million.

19:19.492 --> 19:24.163 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He has a very short remaining
window of time
to put in the remaining $44
million, and we

19:24.196 --> 19:26.065 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
will see if that actually comes
to be.

19:26.098 --> 19:30.736 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And what about in
terms of
reimbursing himself, the
campaign?

19:30.770 --> 19:32.872 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
How does that work and how
typical is that?

19:32.905 --> 19:38.477 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MATEA GOLD: So, the Trump
campaign has used
a lot of Trump properties as he
has been making

19:38.511 --> 19:40.179 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
his bid for the White House.

19:40.212 --> 19:42.948 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They have had events at Trump
hotels.

19:42.982 --> 19:45.751 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
They have their campaign
headquarters in Trump
Tower.

19:45.785 --> 19:51.157 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, under the law, he's not
allowed to let
those companies donate those
services.

19:51.190 --> 19:53.292 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, he does have to reimburse
them for it.

19:53.325 --> 19:58.230 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But his decision to use Trump
companies in
the pursuit of his campaign
means that he's

19:58.264 --> 20:04.203 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
also putting a lot of money back
into his
own companies, more than $9
million to date,

20:04.236 --> 20:06.906 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
including $1 million in
reimbursements last
month.

20:06.939 --> 20:11.644 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, the majority of that money
has gone to
reimburse TAG Air, which is his
private airline.

20:11.677 --> 20:16.415 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now, Matea, you
also wrote
this week that Donald Trump has
decided some

20:16.449 --> 20:22.354 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
days ago to stop holding
big-dollar fund-raising
events for himself and the GOP.

20:22.388 --> 20:24.090 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Why do that?

20:24.123 --> 20:27.827 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MATEA GOLD: So, it is typical at
this point
for the presidential candidates
to get off

20:27.860 --> 20:32.098 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the money circuit and just stick
to campaign
events and rallies.

20:32.131 --> 20:36.902 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But what's unusual is, the Trump
campaign
didn't set up a schedule of
fund-raising events

20:36.936 --> 20:42.741 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for surrogates to continue to
bring in high-dollar
donations to support party in
these final

20:42.775 --> 20:44.243 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
days.

20:44.276 --> 20:48.914 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Clinton has 41 events scheduled
on the books
between now and November 3.

20:48.948 --> 20:51.383 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Trump campaign now says they
have a handful
of events.

20:51.417 --> 20:53.185 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They might do more ad hoc
events.

20:53.219 --> 20:55.621 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But they have taken a very
different approach
to this.

20:55.654 --> 20:59.725 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They said that they are raising
a lot of money
online, some of which will go to
the partly,

20:59.758 --> 21:05.264 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but the majority of their
efforts right now
are on -- is on making his case
to voters.

21:05.297 --> 21:09.435 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, finally,
Matea, you were
talking to us about what you
have noted in

21:09.468 --> 21:16.442 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
terms of how Clinton is raising
big sums of
money from groups that were,
frankly, enabled

21:16.475 --> 21:21.180 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to give money by that famous
Supreme Court
decision Citizens United.

21:21.213 --> 21:22.948 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MATEA GOLD: Right.

21:22.982 --> 21:27.553 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
One thing that is such a
dramatic storyline
in the money race, I think, this
year is the

21:27.586 --> 21:34.193 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
full embrace by Clinton of super
PACs, which
were really entities that
President Obama

21:34.226 --> 21:39.832 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
was very reluctant to support
and use to his
reelection advantage.

21:39.865 --> 21:45.337 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, by contrast, Clinton, from
the very beginning
of her race, made it clear that
she wanted

21:45.371 --> 21:48.107 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
donors to support these groups.

21:48.140 --> 21:52.444 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Because of that, she's been able
to raise,
in conjunction with super PACs
and the party,

21:52.478 --> 21:55.147 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
$1.1 billion in pursuit of the
White House.

21:55.181 --> 21:59.585 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, finally, you
said that
you were surprised the Democrats
have raised

21:59.618 --> 22:01.687 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
as much money as they have this
cycle.

22:01.720 --> 22:05.491 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MATEA GOLD: Well, I don't think
anyone would
have predicted when the cycle
started that

22:05.524 --> 22:07.259 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Democrats would win at the money
race.

22:07.293 --> 22:11.964 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But we have seen that the super
PACs that
have formed to support Trump
have not been

22:11.997 --> 22:13.232 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
very well-organized.

22:13.265 --> 22:16.435 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They have gotten conflicting
messages from
the campaign.

22:16.468 --> 22:21.540 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, because of that, donors
have been reluctant,
until recently, to write big
checks.

22:21.574 --> 22:25.110 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Because the Democrats were so
organized on
the big-money front, they have
been able to

22:25.144 --> 22:30.316 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
collect large checks from the
very beginning
of this race, and now they have
the resources

22:30.349 --> 22:32.585 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to use that money in the final
stretch.

22:32.618 --> 22:35.087 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: A remarkable set
of stories.

22:35.120 --> 22:37.056 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Nobody follows this more closely
than you
do.

22:37.089 --> 22:40.826 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Matea Gold with The Washington
Post, we thank
you.

22:40.859 --> 22:48.100 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MATEA GOLD: Thanks, Judy.

22:48.133 --> 22:54.974 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: More than ever
before, a
big part of this election
campaign has played

22:55.007 --> 22:56.809 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
itself out on social media.

22:56.842 --> 23:01.280 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
No doubt the candidates and
their campaigns
have tried to take advantage of
these platforms.

23:01.313 --> 23:05.851 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But there's been a much bigger
role this year
as well for unseen players.

23:05.884 --> 23:08.287 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You might call it the rise of
the bots.

23:08.320 --> 23:11.957 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Miles O'Brien has the story,
part of our weekly
reporting about on the Leading
Edge of science

23:11.991 --> 23:13.792 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and technology.

23:13.826 --> 23:15.894 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HILLARY RODHAM CLINTON (D),
Presidential Candidate:
Donald supported the invasion of
Iraq.

23:15.928 --> 23:17.363 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP (R), Presidential
Candidate:
Wrong.

23:17.396 --> 23:19.598 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HILLARY RODHAM CLINTON: That is
absolutely
proved over and over again.

23:19.632 --> 23:20.599 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DONALD TRUMP: Wrong.

23:20.633 --> 23:21.600 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Wrong.

23:21.634 --> 23:23.402 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
HILLARY RODHAM CLINTON: He
actually...

23:23.435 --> 23:26.472 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Much as we may
wish otherwise,
the race for the Oval Office is
not over.

23:26.505 --> 23:31.710 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But there is already one clear
winner, by
acclamation, Twitter.

23:31.744 --> 23:37.516 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Thanks to a candidate who
prefers campaigning
in 140-character spurts, the
social networking

23:37.549 --> 23:42.054 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
platform has become an essential
political
forum.

23:42.087 --> 23:43.389 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What could go wrong with that?

23:43.422 --> 23:44.390 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Plenty.

23:44.423 --> 23:46.191 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Tweeters, beware.

23:46.225 --> 23:49.962 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
FILIPPO MENCZER, Indiana
University: Because
so much of the opinions that we
form and the

23:49.995 --> 23:56.602 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
information that we digest comes
from social
networks and social media, it is
possible

23:56.635 --> 24:00.272 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to try and manipulate the
network to control
opinions.

24:00.306 --> 24:06.345 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Filippo Menczer
is director
of the Center for Complex
Networks and Systems

24:06.378 --> 24:08.414 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
at Indiana University.

24:08.447 --> 24:14.286 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He says the junction of the
political and
computer sciences is a dangerous
place for

24:14.320 --> 24:16.155 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
democracy.

24:16.188 --> 24:21.460 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FILIPPO MENCZER: Just like
people have tried
to influence elections forever
without social

24:21.493 --> 24:24.963 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
media, why wouldn't they also
try with social
media?

24:24.997 --> 24:29.068 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Just like any other tool and
technology, it
can be used for good things and
it can also

24:29.101 --> 24:31.070 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
be manipulated or abused.

24:31.103 --> 24:37.743 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Menczer and his
team are researching
the shadowy world of bots,
software programmed

24:37.776 --> 24:40.846 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to mimic humans and engage with
them.

24:40.879 --> 24:43.015 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You probably encounter bots all
the time

24:43.048 --> 24:44.583 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ACTRESS: What's my day look
like?

24:44.616 --> 24:45.984 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
COMPUTER VOICE: Not bad.

24:46.018 --> 24:47.252 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Only two meetings today.

24:47.286 --> 24:49.455 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Whether it's
Apple's Siri.

24:49.488 --> 24:51.323 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ACTOR: Alexa, play rock music.

24:51.357 --> 24:53.025 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
COMPUTER VOICE: Rock music.

24:53.058 --> 24:54.760 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Amazon's Alexa.

24:54.793 --> 24:56.562 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ACTOR: Alexa, stop.

24:56.595 --> 25:01.800 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Or the chat box
that pops up
offering advice when your cable
TV is on the

25:01.834 --> 25:03.035 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
fritz.

25:03.068 --> 25:06.004 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
A good one is hard to
differentiate from a
real person.

25:06.038 --> 25:07.873 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And that's the trouble.

25:07.906 --> 25:13.178 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Clever bots, employed in a
stealthy, strategic
manner, can put a virtual finger
on the scale

25:13.212 --> 25:14.980 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of political discourse.

25:15.013 --> 25:20.486 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Bots generated a huge volume of
tweets pro
and con during the Brexit vote
in the United

25:20.519 --> 25:21.653 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Kingdom.

25:21.687 --> 25:26.392 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They also promoted candidates in
the 2014
India elections.

25:26.425 --> 25:33.699 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ISIS uses bots to amplify
propaganda by creating
thousands of phony accounts.

25:33.732 --> 25:40.439 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FILIPPO MENCZER: It's like very
easy to create
one or 10 or 100 or 1,000
accounts controlled

25:40.472 --> 25:46.044 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
by that campaign and make it
look like these
are just regular people who are
expressing

25:46.078 --> 25:47.846 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
their freedom of speech.

25:47.880 --> 25:54.686 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Bots first reared
their ugly
heads in U.S. presidential
politics in 2012.

25:54.720 --> 26:00.726 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Mitt Romney got caught buying
bots when he
gained more than 140,000
followers in two

26:00.759 --> 26:02.628 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
days.

26:02.661 --> 26:07.232 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For a few dollars, anyone can
buy a few thousand
bots that can be deployed to
strengthen your

26:07.266 --> 26:09.001 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Twitter prowess.

26:09.034 --> 26:14.239 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But this go-round, the bots are
doing much
more than providing artificial
popularity.

26:14.273 --> 26:17.609 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Phil Howard is a professor of
the Internet
at Oxford University.

26:17.643 --> 26:21.713 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PHIL HOWARD, Oxford University:
You program
the bots that are following you
to repeat

26:21.747 --> 26:23.549 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
your message.

26:23.582 --> 26:28.253 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what happens is that a
larger and larger
number of people see the
retweets and think,

26:28.287 --> 26:31.557 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
this is an important position
paper or this
is a great new idea.

26:31.590 --> 26:35.928 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP: You're talking
about taking
out ISIS, but you were there and
you were

26:35.961 --> 26:37.696 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
secretary of state when it was a
little infant.

26:37.729 --> 26:42.201 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Howard analyzed
tweets during
the first presidential debate.

26:42.234 --> 26:49.208 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He found bots were behind
one-fifth of pro-Clinton
Twitter traffic, and nearly
one-third of pro-Trump

26:49.241 --> 26:51.009 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
tweets.

26:51.043 --> 26:54.746 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PHIL HOWARD: The real problem
here is that
not all users can tell when the
content that

26:54.780 --> 26:58.884 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
comes up in their social media
feed is actually
generated by these bots.

26:58.917 --> 27:03.522 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's very difficult to know what
the overall
impact is on public opinion, but
we do know

27:03.555 --> 27:07.759 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that most Americans can't
distinguish these
bots from real users.

27:07.793 --> 27:14.333 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: It's hard enough
for computer
scientists and, for that matter,
Twitter itself.

27:14.366 --> 27:20.973 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The company admits 8.5 percent
of its accounts
are updated with no discernible
human action.

27:21.006 --> 27:26.745 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But that includes useful
applications like
TweetDeck, as well as harmful
bots.

27:26.778 --> 27:28.947 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Finding them is a challenge.

27:28.981 --> 27:32.084 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Menczer and his team are working
on this.

27:32.117 --> 27:37.856 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They visualize Twitter traffic,
helping them
find accounts that look and act
suspiciously

27:37.890 --> 27:39.391 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
nonhuman.

27:39.424 --> 27:42.361 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
FILIPPO MENCZER: Very often,
there are patterns
that we can still discern.

27:42.394 --> 27:47.099 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They're not necessarily easy for
the human
eye, but, sometimes, the
machine-learning

27:47.132 --> 27:52.504 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
algorithms, by looking at over
1,000 features,
they can recognize some patterns
that make

27:52.538 --> 27:55.307 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
one particular account similar
to other bots.

27:55.340 --> 28:00.679 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: The result is a
Web site called
BotOrNot, which analyzes Twitter
accounts

28:00.712 --> 28:06.418 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
based on the frequency of
tweets, the type
of networks and friends, and the
sentiment

28:06.451 --> 28:08.220 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the tweets convey.

28:08.253 --> 28:12.758 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This Twitterbot account simply
repeats pro-Hillary
Reddit postings.

28:12.791 --> 28:16.261 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BotOrNot predicts it is 70
percent likely
to be a bot.

28:16.295 --> 28:20.198 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PHIL HOWARD: One of the fun
things about studying
bots is that it's very difficult
based on

28:20.232 --> 28:24.169 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the code alone to predict what
they will do.

28:24.202 --> 28:28.807 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And even designers can't always
predict what
a bot will do.

28:28.840 --> 28:31.076 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Brad Hayes can
attest to that.

28:31.109 --> 28:34.846 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He is a postdoctoral associate
at MIT.

28:34.880 --> 28:40.953 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He read a Boston Globe article
that concluded
Donald Trump speaks at the level
of a fourth-grader.

28:40.986 --> 28:43.689 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
To him, that sounded like good
grist for some
Twitterbot fun.

28:43.722 --> 28:45.457 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
BRAD HAYES, Postdoctoral
Associate, Massachusetts
Institute of Technology: I went
to work, and

28:45.490 --> 28:50.662 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I created this bot, and I went
through and
grabbed all of the transcripts I
could find

28:50.696 --> 28:56.802 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
from his speeches, the
Republican debates,
from his Twitter feed, basically
anything,

28:56.835 --> 29:01.707 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
any kind of Donald Trump
information, things
that he has said, such that I
could train

29:01.740 --> 29:03.542 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the statistical model on that.

29:03.575 --> 29:09.181 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MILES O'BRIEN: His bot,
DeepDrumpf, doesn't
understand language, per se, but
rather detects

29:09.214 --> 29:11.283 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
patterns in the sequence of
letters.

29:11.316 --> 29:14.786 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP: A lot of things
are going on
