And no one is spared.

47:19.904 --> 47:20.871 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What set you off?

47:20.905 --> 47:22.339 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What are you responding to?

47:22.373 --> 47:23.641 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

47:23.674 --> 47:26.377 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL BEATTY: I'm just kind of
responding to
myself, I guess.

47:26.410 --> 47:31.949 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's not like there is some
impetus that's
like, oh, I have got to write
about that.

47:31.982 --> 47:34.585 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's just stuff that I have been
thinking
about for a long time.

47:34.618 --> 47:40.057 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I just have been thinking
about segregation
for some reason, no -- I think I
had read

47:40.091 --> 47:44.361 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
something about somebody saying,
oh, black
people were better off under
segregation.

47:44.395 --> 47:48.399 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I just went, oh, it would be
so fun to
try to

47:48.432 --> 47:51.836 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
see how segregation would work
now, in a weird
kind of guise.

47:51.869 --> 47:57.675 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: So your
character, nameless
character, young black man, he
tries to resegregate

47:57.708 --> 47:58.809 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
his city, in a sense.

47:58.843 --> 47:59.810 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
PAUL BEATTY: Yes.

47:59.844 --> 48:00.811 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

48:00.845 --> 48:01.812 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: In order to save
it, right?

48:01.846 --> 48:02.813 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
PAUL BEATTY: Yes.

48:02.847 --> 48:04.682 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Strangely enough.

48:04.715 --> 48:07.618 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL BEATTY: He doesn't know
that he's doing
that, and that the city is
already segregated.

48:07.651 --> 48:09.854 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: It is de facto --
it is segregated.

48:09.887 --> 48:11.188 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL BEATTY: In many different
ways.

48:11.222 --> 48:14.024 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes, yes, as is
much of our
life today still.

48:14.058 --> 48:15.826 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
PAUL BEATTY: Exactly.

48:15.860 --> 48:20.297 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's interesting in the book how
acknowledging
that you're being segregated
changes your

48:20.331 --> 48:22.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
behavior a little bit.

48:22.099 --> 48:30.407 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: But it allows you
to look at
every black piety, at every
liberal piety.

48:30.441 --> 48:33.844 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's easy in a way to kind of
skewer out-and-out
racism.

48:33.878 --> 48:34.845 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
PAUL BEATTY: Yes.

48:34.879 --> 48:36.147 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Yes.

48:36.180 --> 48:36.847 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: But you're doing
-- you are
getting everybody.

48:36.881 --> 48:38.816 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
PAUL BEATTY: Yes.

48:38.849 --> 48:44.522 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think it's -- I'm not very
pious about anything,
fortunately, but I'm skewering
myself first.

48:44.555 --> 48:49.994 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I'm skewering things that I care
about and
things that are important to me
and then just

48:50.027 --> 48:51.829 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
my own foibles.

48:51.862 --> 48:54.899 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For me, it's just this stuff
that I'm thinking
about, like these absurdities in
the way we

48:54.932 --> 48:57.201 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
talk about race, class, culture,
education,
politics.

48:57.234 --> 48:58.235 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: What absurdities?

48:58.269 --> 48:59.970 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What do we get wrong?

49:00.004 --> 49:02.039 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL BEATTY: We get it all
wrong.

49:02.072 --> 49:03.808 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
There's no right.

49:03.841 --> 49:07.511 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think that is part of it,
is, like,
we think that there is this
weird utopian

49:07.545 --> 49:11.715 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
endgame to life, not just racial
politics.

49:11.749 --> 49:14.118 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And for me, it's a weird way to
try to live
life.

49:14.151 --> 49:18.856 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it's not to say that we
shouldn't aspire
to those things.

49:18.889 --> 49:24.161 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So a thing I have been hearing
about lately
is some people always say, oh,
it's hard to

49:24.195 --> 49:25.329 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
talk about race.

49:25.362 --> 49:26.497 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We can't have the discussion.

49:26.530 --> 49:28.766 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I'm, like, well, what does that
really mean?

49:28.799 --> 49:33.771 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I don't understand what that
discussion is
and where this metaphorical
table -- you know,

49:33.804 --> 49:34.939 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
we have got to come to the
table.

49:34.972 --> 49:36.340 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I don't know where these tables
are.

49:36.373 --> 49:37.675 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

49:37.708 --> 49:39.443 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL BEATTY: So, yes, I get to
set my own
table a little bit.

49:39.476 --> 49:43.013 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: At the same time,
though, of
course, these are very serious
issues.

49:43.047 --> 49:50.221 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In your book, the narrator's
father is shot
by police in an area around Los
Angeles, and

49:50.254 --> 49:51.222 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
that's very real stuff.

49:51.255 --> 49:52.523 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
PAUL BEATTY: Yes.

49:52.556 --> 49:53.958 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: But your approach
is completely
through humor.

49:53.991 --> 49:57.228 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL BEATTY: Yes, through humor
and through
my own experience.

49:57.261 --> 50:00.564 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, like, the shooting is
something that's
sort of personal to me.

50:00.598 --> 50:03.767 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It wasn't like, oh, people are
getting shot,
let me write about that.

50:03.801 --> 50:07.271 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I'm really starting from myself,
and I'm not
starting from current events or
what it is

50:07.304 --> 50:10.741 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in the news or some "TIME"
magazine sidebar
about this stuff.

50:10.774 --> 50:12.543 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Are we too
squeamish?

50:12.576 --> 50:17.781 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I was thinking to myself, one of
the problems
I have even in quoting from the
book is your

50:17.815 --> 50:19.917 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
very liberal use of the N-word.

50:19.950 --> 50:20.918 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
PAUL BEATTY: Yes.

50:20.951 --> 50:21.919 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Yes.

50:21.952 --> 50:22.920 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Right?

50:22.953 --> 50:23.921 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We can't sit here and read it.

50:23.954 --> 50:24.955 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We can't quote from it too much.

50:24.989 --> 50:25.956 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Are we too squeamish?

50:25.990 --> 50:27.858 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Are we just not talking
honestly?

50:27.892 --> 50:34.331 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL BEATTY: I think it's like
-- like, when
I used to read poetry, people
would bring

50:34.365 --> 50:36.500 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
me into like some high school to
read.

50:36.533 --> 50:38.502 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I would say the F-word or
something.

50:38.535 --> 50:42.606 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And everybody acts so surprised,
like, oh,
I have never heard this word
before.

50:42.640 --> 50:44.642 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But they're saying it five
minutes later.

50:44.675 --> 50:52.783 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So I think there's a weird --
there's this
line between propriety and how
we really speak

50:52.816 --> 50:54.118 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and how we really think.

50:54.151 --> 50:56.153 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I'm just trying to have fun
with that
stuff.

50:56.186 --> 50:57.788 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And you're talking about the
word (EXPLETIVE
DELETED).

50:57.821 --> 50:59.156 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I can't say the N-word for it.

50:59.189 --> 51:02.226 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I just even let myself say it
because it's
just so ridiculous.

51:02.259 --> 51:08.432 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There is a part of the book
where characters
talking about Mark Twain's
"Huckleberry Finn."

51:08.465 --> 51:10.467 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And that word is all throughout
there.

51:10.501 --> 51:13.604 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And this effort to eras that,
and so it's
weird.

51:13.637 --> 51:18.676 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I'm not sure why we're trying to
erase these
things, why we try to use these
euphemisms

51:18.709 --> 51:19.677 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
all the time.

51:19.710 --> 51:21.312 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Like, what purpose is that
serving?

51:21.345 --> 51:26.183 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Is this kind of
big satire
hard to pull off?

51:26.216 --> 51:29.820 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL BEATTY: Yes, I don't try to
be satirical.

51:29.853 --> 51:32.723 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I just try to get what's in my
head on the
page.

51:32.756 --> 51:34.124 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And that part is hard for me to
do.

51:34.158 --> 51:40.798 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It takes a long, long time to
make it poetic,
somewhat essayistic.

51:40.831 --> 51:43.167 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And just I have a little bit of
an agenda.

51:43.200 --> 51:44.768 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That part is hard to pull off.

51:44.802 --> 51:47.171 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And the book is about a big
scope.

51:47.204 --> 51:52.109 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think everybody focuses on
race, but it's
about a ton of things, and it's
because I

51:52.142 --> 51:56.146 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
just see these things as all
interrelated
and all interwoven in a weird
way.

51:56.180 --> 52:00.384 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And where does
your sense,
where does your love of writing
come from

52:00.417 --> 52:02.052 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
or your need to write?

52:02.086 --> 52:05.956 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL BEATTY: I couldn't tell
you, because
I can't say that I love writing,
but I do

52:05.990 --> 52:08.993 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
love the satisfaction that it
gives me.

52:09.026 --> 52:11.362 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's just -- it's really basic.

52:11.395 --> 52:14.732 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I'm glad I found -- I found that
late in life,
and I'm glad I found it at all.

52:14.765 --> 52:17.534 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: All right, the
new novel is
"The Sellout."

52:17.568 --> 52:18.535 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Paul Beatty, thanks so much.

52:18.569 --> 52:22.873 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL BEATTY: Thanks for having
me, Jeff.

52:22.906 --> 52:28.212 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
